#: app/templates/platform.html:1030
msgid "How many participants do I need before the consensus analysis works?"
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/platform.html:1035
msgid ""
"The clustering algorithm needs enough data to identify meaningful groups."
" In practice, you'll start to see clear patterns from around 30–40 active"
" participants (people who have voted on at least 5 statements). The "
"analysis becomes significantly more reliable with 100+ participants, and "
"very robust at 500+. Each participant needs to vote on at least 5 "
"statements to be included in their cluster."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/platform.html:1040
msgid "Are votes anonymous? Who can see what I voted?"
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/platform.html:1045
msgid ""
"Individual votes are private — no one can see how you specifically voted "
"on any statement. What is visible is the aggregate result: the percentage"
" breakdown of agree/disagree/unsure across all participants, and the "
"cluster groupings. The consensus analysis shows which cluster you belong "
"to, but does not reveal your individual votes to other participants or "
"the discussion host."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/platform.html:1050
msgid "What is a Programme and how does it differ from a discussion?"
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/platform.html:1055
msgid ""
"A discussion is a single conversation on one topic. A Programme is a "
"structured campaign that groups many discussions together — for example, "
"a national consultation on housing policy might have separate discussions"
" on planning, affordability, social housing, and landlord regulation. "
"Programmes support phases (e.g. Listening → Deliberation → "
"Recommendations), themes, and participant cohorts, with a single export "
"of all data."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/platform.html:1060
#, fuzzy
msgid "Can I export the data from my discussion?"
msgstr "ディスカッションを探す"

#: app/templates/platform.html:1065
msgid ""
"Yes. Discussion creators and Programme managers can export all vote data "
"as CSV or JSON — including per-statement results, participant clusters, "
"and cohort breakdowns. This lets you do your own analysis, feed results "
"into reports, or archive everything outside the platform."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/platform.html:1070
msgid ""
"How is Society Speaks different from a standard survey tool like "
"SurveyMonkey?"
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/platform.html:1075
msgid ""
"Survey tools give you aggregate responses — percentages and averages. "
"Society Speaks reveals the <em>structure</em> of opinion: how views "
"cluster, which ideas bridge opposing groups, and where genuine fault "
"lines lie. It's also open to public participation by default, and "
"participants can add their own statements and reasoning — making it a "
"genuine deliberative tool rather than a data collection exercise."
msgstr ""

